\section{Results and conclusion}
The first significant result is the fact that the slot waveguide has much weaker carrier effect than the Si strip waveguides. This is clear from Fig.~\ref{fig:timeResolvesMeasurements}, and also from the $\sigma_n$ parameter, defined in \cite{Lin2007} and shown in Table~\ref{table:results}. This considerably reduces the undesired patterning effects when modulating a real bit pattern. On the other hand, the figure of merit (FOM) that provides the ratio between Kerr effect and TPA is also significantly higher than the strip waveguides, as shown in Table~\ref{table:results}. All these observations can be explained by the fact that in the slot waveguide, a considerable amount of energy travels through the slot layer, which has much weaker TPA carrier effects. The TM mode of the strip waveguide has a higher FOM than the TE because the TM mode also has more energy in the cladding than the TE mode. These results agree with the ones shown in Ref.~\cite{Vallaitis2009} for a polymer-filled vertical slot; however, our system, being made of inorganic materials and only requiring CMOS processes, are expected to provide more robust and stable devices with less temperature constraints.
In conclusion, ultrafast nonlinear measurements show that silicon-nanocrystal-based horizontal slot waveguides show much weaker carrier effects and higher FOM as compared to Si strip waveguides. This makes the slot structure better suited for CMOS-compatible high-speed all-optical processing than simple Si strip waveguides.


%In conclusion, TM horizontal slot waveguides with silicon nanocrystals could be exploited for nonlinear applications thanks to their high nonlinear coefficient not being hindered by the free-carrier limitations. When carrier effects are involved, the speed in optical devices is limited by their recombination time, which is usually in the order of 1\,ns. However with the time resolved measurements we have observed half free-carrier-absorption (FCA) and an order of magnitude lower free-carrier-dispersion (FCD) thanks to the geometry of the slot waveguide. This could be exploited for high speed optical devices with the advantage of being CMOS-compatible.

%Low carrier generation could solve the problems such as . Optical devices
